3. Display the percentage distribution of the data in each year using the pie chart.¶

In [42]:
# using the matplot to plot the pie plot by the function plt.pie
plt.pie(df.year.value_counts(),autopct="%.1f%%",radius=1.0,labels = ["2001","2002","2003","1998","1999","2000","2004","2005","2006","2007","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012"],startangle=10)
#Determining the tite
plt.title("Distribution % of Honey Each Year")
#To show case the legend determining the location and also providing bbox_to_anchor to place the legend in the proper area..
plt.legend(df["year"],loc="upper right",bbox_to_anchor=(1.5,1),labels=["2001","2002","2003","1998","1999","2000","2004","2005","2006","2007","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012"])
plt.show()

4. Plot and Understand the distribution of the variable "price per lb" using displot, and write your findings.¶

In [43]:
# Showing up the displot without Histogram
sns.displot(df["priceperlb"],kind="kde",color="b")
plt.title("Distribution of [Price per lb]")
plt.xlabel("priceperlb ($)")
plt.legend("displot",loc="upper right")
plt.show()
In [44]:
# With Histogram:-
sns.displot(df["priceperlb"],kind="hist",color="blue",kde=True,bins=10)
plt.title("Distribution of [Price per lb]")
plt.xlabel("priceperlb in ($)")
plt.show()

So this plot clearly shows the histogram and the distribution plot, since this plot claims positively skewed¶

So the mean is around (1.6) and which is greater than the median(1.36) so that it was positively skewed....¶

This also signifies kurtosis is going almost sharp¶

By all of these statements it is clear this is not a normal distribution curve.¶

since the priceperlb is the prodvalue/totalprod which will give the value.¶

when the production increases the product value also increases.¶

Most of the priceperlb values lies in the range 1.6 of frequency count of around 175, whereas in the max side holds 4.15 which has low frequency of around 10¶

5. Plot and understand the relationship between the variables 'numcol' and 'prodval' through scatterplot, and write your findings.¶

In [45]:

# Plotted for numcoln and prodvalue with respect to year..
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="numcol",y="prodvalue",color="red")
plt.title("Scatterplot of [numcol & prodvalue]")
plt.xlabel("Number of honey producing colonies")
plt.ylabel("Value of production ($)")
plt.show()

This states that it has the positive linear relationship between the two variables..¶

Which also makes the correlation to be positive¶

This signifies that when number of honey producing colonies increses which also increases productionvalue which is also related to totalproduction..¶

So, this scatter also shows that there are more values in the range of o to 2 and also between 0 to around 20000 in the numcol...¶

The highest numcol is 500000 which holds the value of 7*e7.¶

And also there is no patterned error..¶

6. Plot and understand the relationship between categorical variable 'year' and a numerical variable'prodvalue' through boxplot, and write your findings.¶

In [46]:

plt.title("Box_plot of year and prodvalue")
plt.show()

Since for the year and prodvalue for this holds so many outliers in it.¶

The largest outlier which was in the year 2010¶

All the mean,median & mode value holds in the value of range between 0 and 1..¶

So,this may also states that most of the sellers sell their product at higher side..¶

so the displot of distribution of "numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue' were positvely skewed.¶

So the year vs numcol the most values lies in between 0-20000,¶

year vs yieldpercol the more number of values lies in between 50 - 100 only throughout the year the distribution tend to lies in the same range.¶

year vs totalprod the values lies between 0-2¶

In the same case the prodvalue lies between 0-2.5¶

This pair plot shows that distribution all the data points of years were of this were positively skewed.¶

8. Display the correlation values using a plot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol','total prod', 'stocks', 'price per lb', 'prodvalue')¶

In [48]:
sns.heatmap(df[["numcol", "yieldpercol","totalprod","stocks","priceperlb","prodvalue"]].corr(),annot=True,cmap="magma")
plt.show()

The Top negatively co-related pair¶

1) yieldpercol and priceperlb (-0.36)¶

2) priceperlb and stocks (-0.31)¶

3) priceperlb and totalprod (-0.26)¶

The Top Positively co-related pair¶

1) totalprod and numcol (0.95)¶

2) prodvalue and numcol (0.91) | totalprod and prodvalue (0.91)¶

3) totalprod and stocks (0.88)¶

4) stocks and numcol(0.83)¶

5) stocks and prodvalue(0.73)¶
